<!-- Lesson 02 Example -->
<script>
// Create variables
var input;
var number;

// Input from user
input = prompt("Enter a number:");

// Convert string to number
number = Number(input); // converts the string from the prompt into a number

// Output
document.write("You typed: " + input + "<br>"); // Will be displayed as text on the page
document.write("I can show you what happens when we doubble your number: " + number + "<br>"); // just to explain what is happening and repeat the number for no reason... 
document.write("Double that number is: " + (number * 2)); // divde by 2 with /, add with +, subtract with -
</script>
<!--prompt always gives text (string).

To do math, convert the string into a number with Number(...), parseInt(...), or parseFloat(...). But i dont know the difference yet.

alert = popup, document.write = page, console.log = console.

" " = string (text), no quotes = number.

+ with numbers = addition, + with strings = join text. * with numbers = multiplication. / with numbers = division.

Invalid conversion = NaN (Not a Number). If the user put a letter in the prompt-->